### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

So, it is with little controversy and _good intent_ that I start with the biggest business-related reason a change like this should be considered. Angular is not doing so hot on the StackOverflow annual surveys, coming in as the "most dreaded" framework for 3 years in a row and counting. A glance at the npm stats is eye-opening.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55965128/225167579-63b22951-a718-41e1-b9ea-04a3fc476a78.png)

I think this is actually a shame, as Google hires brilliant people and leads the world's internet in almost every other way. I think the Angular team could really benefit from considering changes that would earn some reputation among the developers who are clamoring for a better DX. With the introduction of signals, you've already started seeing some positive light shone on the framework among both the common community and the influential voices in it. Let's capitalize on that while we have the momentum!

The popular trend is moving toward simplified code with less boilerplate, and functional components have been a great way to achieve that. React is the obvious example here, despite some criticisms of its hooks. Vue3 came next with its setup scripts, dramatically reducing its boilerplate. And now we're in a new era of front end frameworks, where Solid is making its debut with functional components that only run once, while subsequent renders are centered around signals.

Angular brings a unique perspective to development that may be overlooked and undervalued, specifically because people don't look long enough to see it. Some of its notable strengths are _prescribed architecture_, _resilience to bugs_, and its _powerful CLI_. Let's see if we can get away with sprinkling a little bit of DX without sacrificing any of that! I think functional components would be a very interesting place to start.

### Proposed solution

The following demonstrates one possible idea for how this could be implemented in Angular. Please keep in mind, this is very raw and unrefined - the primary purpose of the feature request is to get some feedback and discussion brewing in both the Angular team and the greater dev community.

Another note just for transparency, I'm out of practice when it comes to Angular, so a lot of my experience may be more reflective of what I'm used to seeing in React/Next and Vue/Nuxt. If this discussion gains traction, I will be more than happy to refresh myself on the more advanced usage and contribute any way I can.

```ts
import { setupComponent, signal, EventEmitter } from '@angular/core';
import { HeroService } from '../../services/hero.service';

export const define = setupComponent({
  selector: 'app-hero-list',
  inject: { HeroService },
});

const HeroListComponent = ({
  ngComponent,
  ngInputs,
  ngOutputs,
  ngPrivate,
  ngTemplate,
  HeroService,
}) => {

  const title = signal<string>('Hero List');
  const selectEvent: EventEmitter<Hero> = new EventEmitter();
  
  const heroes = signal<Hero[]>([]);
  const selectedHero = signal<Hero | null>(null);
  const selectHero = (hero: Hero) => {
    selectedHero.set(hero);
    selectEvent.emit(hero);
  };
  
  HeroService.fetchHeroes().subscribe((resultHeroes: Hero[]) => {
    heroes.set(resultHeroes);
  });

  return ngComponent(
    ngInputs({ title }),
    ngOutputs({ selectEvent }),
    ngPrivate({ heroes, selectHero, selectedHero }),
    ngTemplate`
    	<h2>{{ title() }}</h2>

      <p><em>Select a hero from the list to see details.</em></p>
      <ul>
        <li *ngFor="let hero of heroes()">
          <button type="button" (click)="selectHero(hero)">
            {{ hero.name }}
          </button>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <app-hero-detail *ngIf="selectedHero()" [hero]="selectedHero()"></app-hero-detail>
    `,
  );

};

export default HeroListComponent;
```

This part could happen under the hood, but it could be important for testing's sake:
```ts
import HeroListComponent, { define } from 'heroList.component';
define(HeroListComponent);
```

I think the code more or less speaks for itself, but here are some things to note:

- The `define` exported function would be replaceable with a mock version, which would inject mock dependencies like that HeroService.
- Notice all dependencies are destructured from the params instead of being imported directly. This is intentional, because such a pattern tends to be slightly easier to test.
- Opting out of decorators like this may be more attractive to conscientious devs who don't like the idea of supporting a [non-standard feature](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-decorators) using compiler magic to force it to work across platforms.
- You may even consider supporting JSX here... but on the other side of things, I imagine `ngTemplateUrl('./heroList.component.html')` could be an option to maintain the separation as well. Worth noting, I don't think a lot of modern developers value markup separation at this point, because the [concerns are separated differently these days](https://levelup.gitconnected.com/modern-day-separation-of-concerns-74e79ff87767). It does seem to be something that many Angular advocates seem to like, though, so it's a matter of balancing your existing users against appealing to new users.

### Alternatives considered

I don't know how applicable alternatives are in this circumstance, but I suppose the core issue is DX. I do have a laundry list of other items that could make DX a little friendlier.

- Add support for [HOCs](https://reactjs.org/docs/higher-order-components.html)
- Add support for [fallthrough attributes](https://vuejs.org/guide/components/attrs.html)
- Give more control over the root element, for example, with CSS `:host`
- Simplify state management - see [Pinia](https://pinia.vuejs.org/), [MobX](https://mobx.js.org/)
- First class support for [context](https://reactjs.org/docs/context.html)
- Services could be more functional also

With enough discussion, it may warrant opening new issues for any/all of these bullet points...

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

I do a lot with data binding and these days making a new component means I set changeDetection to ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush and set a private cdr:ChangeDetectorRef variable in the constructor. 

I then create a Refresh() function that checks if the component is setup and if so will call the cdr.detectChanges() function. 

This is great performance wise because I can change a variety of component properties and trigger Refresh when I want.

The down side is that changes to @Input variables don't necessarily trigger an update.

So I end up having to implement a private variable to hold data in, and use a setter and getter where the setter in addition to setting the variable will trigger a change detection.

```
private _someVar:string = 'helloWorld';
@Input(someVar)
set someVar(value:string) {
  this._someVar = value;
  this.Refresh();
}
get someVar():string {
  return this._someVar;
}
```

I realize that using OnPush means I'm basically signing up for the hassle of these setters.  But it would be nice in an OnPush setup to have an @Input variant that is aware of this setup.

### Proposed solution

My thinking was something along the lines of:

```
private _someVar:string ='Hello World';
@OnPushInput(()=>{this.onRefresh()} ) someVar:string; 
```
or
```
@OnPushInput({onUpdate:()=>{this.onRefresh()}, saveAs:'_someVar'} ) someVar:string; 
```
That would transpile into the equivalent setter and getter for someVar that would store in private variable _someVar. 

The IDEs would ideally recognize someVar in templates as bindable and I would have the option in the controller code to set this._someVar="something" without triggering an update, or setting this.someVar = "something" which would trigger an update.

@OnPushInput would be for when you want input but not necessarily bind output.

@OnPushIO would be an addition evolution of this idea and would do the same thing as @OnPushInput but would additionally internally have a someVarChange:EventEmitter<somevar's type> event emitter which emits this.someVar (getter version) when the setter is used.

The idea would be to have:
```
private _someVar:string = 'HelloWorld';
@OnPushIO({saveAs:'_someVar',onUpdate:()=>{this.Refresh();}) someVar:string;
```
This would mean, setup someVar with a getter/setter and emitter so that it is two-way bindable.

### Alternatives considered

I know javascript has a defineProperty function, but that seems like overkill.

The proposed:
```
private _someVar:string = 'HelloWorld';
@OnPushIO({saveAs:'_someVar',onUpdate:()=>{this.Refresh();}) someVar:string;
```
Right now is:
```
private _someVar:string = 'Hello World';
@Input()
someVar(val:string) {
 this._val = val;
 this.someValChange.emit(this._val);
 this.Refresh();
}
get someVar():string {
 return this._val;
}
@Output()
someValChange = new EventEmitter<string>;
```
One of the rules of thumb in refactoring is if you are doing the same thing three or more times encapsulate the repeated functionality in a function and call it from the same place.

I do apologize if something like this exists, but I have not really seen it referred to in documentation or in discussions about @Input and @Output. Hence the feature request.

